<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unless you are already immersed in the mini-series A Woman Named Jackie
about Jackie Kennedy/Onassis (8.00 with more at 10.40, ITV) this is not a
night for fiction lovers. Bags of fact programmes, though. Out Of Darkness
is the first in a series which promises a 'critical' look at the efforts
being made to re-shape African societies, opening with Angola (7.50 BBC2).
The Velvet Claw is another new series (8.30 BBC1), this one using animation
and computer graphics to illustrate the sort of carnivores which dominated
the earth once the dinosaurs disappeared.
This week's programme in C4's Travellers' Tales shows comedian Jimmy Tingle
driving from Canada to Mexico in a Ford convertible (9.00).
Panorama (9.30 BBC1) considers the decline of British racing, asking whether
the crisis stems from lack of business sense or the unwillingness of bookies
to pay their share. This will need to be good to match BBC2's recent
excellent series on the same subject.
Barry Norman returns with Film 92 (10.10 BBC1) and BBC2's arts magazine The
Late Show comes back (11.15) with a profile of novelist Jeanette Winterson.
</TEXT>
