<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 92 / City regulation under fire
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
REGULATION of many financial institutions continues to be ineffective,
bureaucratic and costly, although it is better regarded than it was two
years ago, according to a survey of 100 senior City professionals by Access
Opinions.
Among the main findings are that the City believes that customers of
financial services are dissatisfied with the effectiveness of the regulatory
system, and the self regulatory organisations are perceived as being less
effective now than in 1990 in protecting private investors.
The Investment Management Regulatory Organisation (Imro) has seen
perceptions deteriorate - 64 per cent now say that Imro is ineffectual
compared with 30 per cent two years ago. The Securities and Investments
Board is better regarded than it was in 1990, with 62 per cent very or
fairly satisfied compared with 52 per cent two years ago.
City Regulation. Access Opinions, 7 The Sanctuary, Parliament Square, London
SW1P 3JS. Pounds 19.95.
</TEXT>
