<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 92 / Discrepancies in audit fees reported
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AUDIT fees paid by quoted companies over the last year were
substantially higher than those paid by private companies, a survey has
found.
In companies with turnover of between Pounds 1bn and Pounds 3bn there was no
difference in fees between public companies and private companies, but in
companies with turnover of less than Pounds 1bn fees for quoted companies
were much higher.
The analysis is based on the audit fees disclosed in the latest sets of
accounts of a sample of 4,000 private companies and more than 200 public
companies by JDH Consultants, a Glasgow-based organisation.
The average audit fee for quoted companies with a turnover of about Pounds
1m was Pounds 9,000, three times the level for private companies. For those
with turnovers of Pounds 10m, the fees were twice those of private companies
at Pounds 22,000 and for those with turnovers of Pounds 100m, fees were
three times the level at Pounds 150,000. For public companies with turnover
of around Pounds 1bn, fees were Pounds 650,000 against Pounds 470,000 for
private companies.
Auditors claim that it is impossible to make comparisons of audit fees based
simply on turnover because so many other factors determine the fee.
However, the study shows a consistent connection between size and fees, and
a clear differentiation between public and private companies.
The survey highlights that there are also wide variations in audit fees
charged by private companies by industrial sector. For companies with sales
of around Pounds 100m, fees were greatest in printing and publishing,
mechanical engineering and textiles, and lowest for the wholesale and retail
trade and food and drink manufacturers.
It also shows the dominance of auditing even in small companies by the
larger accountancy firms. Although there were 1,674 different auditing firms
for the 4,000 private companies, 29 per cent by number and 58 per cent by
fee were controlled by just 12 firms.
Two Midlands accountancy firms are merging to become a regional firm with 16
partners and fee income of about Pounds 6m. Cooper-Parry, Watson, Sowter &amp;
Co, based in Derby, and Prior &amp; Palmer of Nottingham will become
Cooper-Parry, Prior &amp; Palmer.
Report of Audit Fees of UK Private Limited Companies. JDH Consultants, 11
Clydebrae Drive, Bothwell, Glasgow G71 8SB. Pounds 75.
</TEXT>
