<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 92 / BR to revive old routes to London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL is working on plans for a package of new rail services linking
the south and west Midlands with London from May next year.
One proposal is likely to put the expanding town of Kidderminster in
Hereford and Worcester on the InterCity map for the first time.
Another will see the re-introduction of direct passenger services between
London and Birmingham on the old Great Western Railway line through High
Wycombe and Banbury.
The plan to give Kidderminster an InterCity link with London is unexpected
because it comes when other InterCity services, such as those to Shrewsbury,
Cleethorpes and Blackpool, are being cut.
BR is understood to be planning one InterCity 125 service early each morning
from Kidderminster to London Paddington via Worcester and Oxford with a
return service each evening.
In addition, Regional Railways and Network SouthEast plan to run one of BR's
new Networker Turbo express trains from Birmingham Snow Hill to
Kidderminster, Worcester, Oxford and London Paddington each morning, with a
return trip in the afternoon.
Kidderminster's InterCity service will be at the expense of one of the two
daily InterCity services running each way between Hereford and London.
In its place, Hereford passengers will be provided with a Sprinter train
connecting with the Kidderminster service at Worcester. BR also plans to
increase direct links between Hereford and London by introducing some of its
new Networker Turbo express trains to the route.
Regional Railways said of BR's other big innovation - reviving through
services on the former Great Western line - that it expected the services to
make money in spite of the recession. 'We are in the business of starting
services up, not closing them down.'
The line fell into disuse for through services after the electrification of
the alternative route running from London Euston to Birmingham New Street
through Rugby and Coventry. Now, Regional Railways and Network SouthEast
plan to introduce four trains a day each way between Birmingham Snow Hill
and London Marylebone using Networker Turbo express trains.
</TEXT>
