<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 92 / Travelling without let or hindrance: The new technological
rigours behind relaxed passport controls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW technology and initiatives to ease border controls could make Her
Britannic Majesty's demand - inscribed in every British passport - for
passage 'without let or hindrance' a thing of the past.
From one end of the European Community to another, frontier formalities are
being lifted. Brussels is encouraging member states to allow unhindered
travel without officials giving even a cursory glance at passports.
Britain will not be so accommodating. The government last week reserved the
right to scrutinise documents at British ports of entry, although it has
pledged to relax controls on EC nationals.
Community officials are trying to solve the British dilemma: how EC citizens
can be identified without queues and delays at passport desks.
Travel industry analysts say the problem offers Britain the opportunity to
use new technology to ease immigration procedures not only for Community
nationals but also for frequent visitors from countries such as the US and
Japan.
Mr Dan White, an analyst for County NatWest, said the Home Office should
pursue a scheme pioneered at Amsterdam's Schiphol airport, where passengers
can avoid queues by using 'smart cards' which can be read by computers.
Dutch travellers who use the airport at least five times a year can opt for
a card containing passport and fingerprint details. The software could be
installed at any EC airport.
BAA, the UK airports operator, is discussing the introduction of such
systems with the Home Office but says it could be some time before 'smart
cards' are available to British travellers.
Immigration officials are also looking at a US scheme which is due to
undergo tests at New York's JFK and Newark airports next month. It relies on
biometric technology, which stores the 'hand geography' of frequent
travellers.
At US immigration passports of computer-registered passengers will be
scanned, while a second system will read their palms to verify that the
passport is not being used by another person. The new European Community
passports will be compatible with this system.
The scheme could cut waiting times at airports, but British officials
believe it would be costly and difficult to introduce at sea ports.
The Home Office is co-operating with a separate US initiative to ease
congestion for airline passengers crossing the Atlantic. From next year all
passengers from London's Heathrow or Gatwick airports to the US will pass
through US immigration before leaving Britain.
US Immigration and Naturalisation Service officials will 'admit' passengers
to the US before they depart. The move is based on a scheme launched at
Shannon in the Irish Republic in 1988 and follows extensive tests in the UK
last year.
The scheme has prompted calls for reciprocal arrangements in the US for
travellers flying to Heathrow airport, where the arrival of several
transatlantic flights between 7am and 9am can lead to delays at passport
control.
'We'd like to see the same pre-inspection immigration in the US,' said Mr
Joe Brancatelli, executive editor of Frequent Flier, the New York magazine.
'There are a lot of complaints about Heathrow,' he added. 'The lines can be
impossible and Paris can also be nasty. We haven't seen advances that should
have been in place five or six years ago. Only Frankfurt seems to be
efficient.'
In London, minimum standards introduced by the Home Office for passport
control show that US passengers will continue to face longer delays than
their EC counterparts. The targets suggest that non-EC passengers should
wait no longer than 10 minutes at immigration while EC citizens can expect a
three-minute wait.
The Home Office said it would consider proposals to pre-inspect passports of
UK-bound passengers in the US. But an airline would have to apply for such a
scheme before formal negotiations could begin.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
