<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 92 / Consumer confidence 'has sunk'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMER confidence in Britain has 'collapsed' in the four months since the
Conservatives' election victory, and household spending intentions are at a
lower level than at any time in the past 18 months according to a survey to
be issued today.
PA Cambridge Economic Consultants says in its latest quarterly survey of
household economic confidence that the main uncertainty undermining consumer
confidence appears to be the fear of increased interest rates.
'This has extremely serious implications for the prospects of an upturn in
consumers' expenditure,' the private-sector economic research group says.
'The very fact that an increase is possible is enough to dampen the
likelihood of a recovery in consumption this year. If interest rates are
forced up in practice, the implications for economic recovery could be even
more severe.'
The survey was unveiled as Labour launched a fresh attack on Mr John Major's
'seven broken promises' since election predictions of an early end to
recession.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, said the seven promises included the
promises of a post-election economic recovery and of a 'classless society'.
Mr Major had also pledged an end to most home repossessions and provision of
places on Youth Training and Work Experience schemes along with extra
spending on a range of public services.
The Tories, he said, were guilty of a 'breach of trust with the electorate',
and even their own supporters had become disillusioned.
The 'broken promises' theme will dominate the opposition's campaigning over
the autumn, with the message being taken to constituencies as well as being
driven home in Westminster.
'Ministers must now admit they misled the public and tell us how they will
change policy to honour their promises,' Mr Brown said.
</TEXT>
