<HEADLINE>
FT  07 SEP 92 / Summit condemns ethnic cleansing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM KEELING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JAKARTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) yesterday ended its summit in Jakarta with a
communique condemning 'the obnoxious policy of ethnic cleansing by Serbs in
Bosnia-Hercegovina'.
The Yugoslav delegation, representing Serbia and Montenegro, rejected the
condemnation, saying the movement had 'changed the document after adoption'.
Before the final draft, the communique had not singled out the Serbs as
responsible for ethnic cleansing. The Yugoslavs called the changes
'deplorable', insisting 'all three sides to the conflict, including Croats
and Moslems in Bosnia-Hercegovina, are involved in such practices'. Some
member states want to expel Yugoslavia. Croatia, Slovenia and
Bosnia-Hercegovina re-applied for full or observer status.
