FT  05 SEP 92 / Gardening: Plant of the Week - Fuchsia Lady Thumb
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARTHUR HELLYER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An upright yet dwarf hardy fuchsia which is specially suitable for window
boxes and containers because of its compact growth. The neatly-formed
flowers have carmine sepals and a white corolla, a very keen and distinctive
contrast. This variety could be paired with Tom Thumb which is similar in
height and habit and has scarlet and mauve flowers. All hardy fuchsias can
be planted outdoors and if covered with two inches of soil for protection
are unlikely to be killed by frost. In many winters stems may be killed to
ground level but should be removed in spring when new growths will appear
rapidly from the roots.
