<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DERIVATIVES market experienced a volatile but busy end of the account
session as early strength gave way to profit-taking and a retreat caused by
poor economic data from the US, writes Joel Kibazo.
In futures, September opened strongly at 2,420 but after a brief move up
when it touched 2,423 and pulled the underlying cash market higher,
profit-taking set in leading it to gently drift lower.
The release of disappointing employment figures from the US after 1.30pm
caused a sharp retreat in the contract and a poor opening on Wall Street,
following the figures caused further weakness. Interest from Goldman Sachs,
which was a buyer of September and a seller of the December contracts helped
produce a rally just before the close.
September closed at 2,377, down 34 on its previous close and around 9 points
above its estimated fair value premium to cash of about 6. Turnover was high
at 14,348 contracts.
Traded options were also busy, with turnover reaching 33,357 lots. The FT-SE
100 option traded 18,066 lots, while Hanson was the busiest stock option
with 1,752 lots.
