FT  05 SEP 92 / Peres says talks best 10 days ever
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Shimon Peres, Israel's foreign minister, said the latest round of Middle
East peace talks in Washington yielded 'the best 10 days ever' in
Israeli-Syrian relations, Reuter reports from Jerusalem.
Mr Lawrence Eagleburger, US acting secretary of state, was similarly
optimistic yesterday, saying there had been important movement in the
US-brokered talks between Israel, Syria, Lebanon, Jordan and the
Palestinians, which adjourned on Thursday.
Mr Peres told Israeli television: 'In the 44 years since the founding of
Israel, there have never been 10 days like these in Syrian-Israeli relations
. . . From the peace standpoint, these have been the best 10 days ever.'
Israel has long seen Syria as its most implacable enemy. It has formally
been at war with Israel since the Jewish state was established in 1948.
However, some Arab delegates expressed disappointment that Israel had not
shown more flexibility. 'We have seen improvement in atmosphere, in tone, in
style, but we haven't seen yet that promise in change concerning substantive
matters,' Mr Mouwafaq al-Allaf, chief Syrian delegate, told reporters.
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, Israeli prime minister, said yesterday both Israel and
Syria had yet to set out their full negotiating positions. 'I don't think
the Syrians have yet shown all their cards, just as we haven't shown all our
cards. We have not revealed what price we are prepared to pay in exchange
for full peace,' he told Israeli television.
The talks had been scheduled to run for a month, but the Israelis have asked
for a 10-day recess for consultations.
</TEXT>
