<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 92 / Dutch sign open skies deal with US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US and the Netherlands signed a liberal 'open skies' accord in
Washington yesterday.
This gives KLM Royal Dutch Airlines essentially unrestricted access to the
aviation market in the US.
The bilateral agreement is the first under Washington's 11-point 'open
skies' initiative, which seeks to exchange freer access to the American
market for similar rights for US carriers abroad.
It comes only months before Europe's January initiation of a single air
transport market, coincides with a fierce transatlantic fare war and is
aimed at pressuring other EC governments to sign similar accords.
Recently, countries such as France and Germany have been seeking to restrict
US carriers' access to their markets, saying they enjoy an unfair advantage.
The deal also coincides with British Airways' controversial attempt to
expand its US market presence through a major equity partnership with the
USAir group.
Calling the deal 'a very significant event in international aviation', US
transportation secretary, Mr Andrew Card, said it represented a model for
market-oriented aviation agreements with other countries.
The pact gives KLM and other Dutch carriers open entry and unrestricted
capacity rights on flights through US international gateways and on to other
US and third-country destinations, widens flexibility in fare-setting and
sets liberal charter and cargo arrangements.
The airlines are allowed to enter freely into open code-sharing arrangements
with other carriers (ticketing connecting flights with partner-airlines
using the flight number or sharing aircraft).
It also includes a pledge for non-discriminatory operation of and access to
computer reservation systems.
Governments are allowed to interfere in fare-setting only in the case of
excessively high or low fares.
Under the deal, US carriers will further widen the already liberal rights
they have enjoyed in Holland for several years.
KLM, 38 per cent owned by the Dutch state, said it was 'extremely pleased'
with the accord, which it expects to boost the importance of Amsterdam's
Schiphol airport as an international air transport hub.
The accord will also allow it to take fuller advantage of its co-operation
with Northwest Airlines, in which it holds a 20 per cent stake.
The Dutch transport minister, Mrs Hanja Maij-Weggen, called it a 'dream
treaty'.
She said: 'We expect it will bring money to our airlines and believe it will
provide an impetus for the further liberalisation of European air
transport.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
