<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 92 / You'll believe Superman can die
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IT WAS morning in America yesterday. But then, a heavy, dark and pendulous
cloud of ominous breadth passed over the national horizon, and remained
suspended over the imaginary city of Metropolis.
There was solemn news, disclosed by the comic book division of Time Warner,
of the imminent demise of Superman, that most winsome and able of
super-heroes, he who once descended from the planet Krypton.
Yes, Superman will die, in issue number 75 of the eponymous comic book, to
be published on November 20, 1992.
The man who was born with a few strokes of a pencil in 1938, and who has
starred in countless books, magazines, movies and television, may be able to
fly faster than a speeding bullet and leap tall buildings in a single bound.
But he has found it impossible to resist the commercial dictates of a mighty
publisher.
In New York last night, Mr Paul Levitz, executive vice-president and
publisher of Time Warner's DC Comics division, finally confirmed the rumours
that had been swirling about the city all day.
Although Superman has generated more than Dollars 1bn of consumer sales over
the past decade, Mr Levitz said the story line would dictate death for the
Man of Steel, come November.
An aide to Mr Levitz explained the scenario: 'There will be a character
called Doomsday, who is like this force of destruction who comes out of the
ground and starts moving in a straight line toward Metropolis. Both Doomsday
and Superman will die after a big battle in front of the headquarters of The
Daily Planet. Clark Kent will also be missing. And Lois Lane, Superman's
fiancee, will be traumatised.'
Superman will die - but will he return? 'I think this is a nice
attention-getting device,' said Mr Levitz. When pressed further, he would
only say: 'Superman, as a multi-media property which is so valuable to Time
Warner, is not going to disappear.'
In Wisconsin, Mr Don Thomas of the Comic Buyers' Guide said he also expected
Superman might well return - somewhere, somehow. 'It's a little difficult to
determine what death means to someone from the planet Krypton,' Mr Thomas
observed.
</TEXT>
