<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 92 / Italy suspends further aid flights to Sarajevo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM, LAURA SILBER and FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME, BELGRADE, GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE ITALIAN government yesterday announced the suspension of further
humanitarian flights to Sarajevo as evidence mounted that the aircraft which
crashed killing its four-man crew near the Bosnian capital on Thursday had
been hit by a missile.
Mr Salvo Ando, Italian defence minister, said yesterday, after a cabinet
meeting: 'The most probable thesis is that the aircraft was shot down.' At
the time of the incident, the G-222 military transport, without armed
escort, was easily identifiable at 10,000 feet on a route normally used for
humanitarian flights. It was carrying blankets to some 380,000 people
trapped by a five-month Serb siege of Sarajevo.
Mr Ando said this suggested that, if the aircraft had been the object of an
attack, a missile was the most likely weapon.
Three of the bodies were recovered by UN rescue teams on Thursday evening;
the fourth was recovered yesterday. From Belgrade, there were reports that
two eye-witnesses had said the aeroplane was hit before it crashed into
mountains controlled by Moslem and Croat forces some 20 miles west of
Sarajevo. A local commander of the Croatian Defence Council yesterday
admitted it had shot at US search and rescue helicopters investigating the
wreckage.
Mr Ando said Italian humanitarian flights would not be resumed 'until we
have found out what happened and, above all, who was responsible'.
UN humanitarian flights into Sarajevo have also been suspended until the
cause of the Italian crash is clear.
In Belgrade, Mr Milan Panic, prime minister of the internationally
unrecognised Yugoslavia, won a no-confidence motion in the federal
parliament by 66 votes to 33. In the debate, MPs had accused the outspoken
prime minister of having betrayed Serbian interests at the London peace
conference last week.
In his lively defence, Mr Panic told the Socialist-dominated parliament that
the London talks had been a turning-point for the unrecognised Yugoslavia.
The no-confidence motion was proposed by members of the Socialist Party and
the Serbian Radical Party, which is headed by Mr Vojislav Seselj, an
ultra-nationalist. He is also commander of a paramilitary wing and is known
as Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic's favourite politician.
However, Mr Milosevic has been increasingly isolated after the failure of an
earlier bid to oust the prime minister.
Meanwhile, in Geneva, the UN launched an urgent appeal for an additional
Dollars 434m (Pounds 218m) 'to avert a looming humanitarian disaster' in the
former Yugoslavia this winter. However, the appeal covers less than half the
Dollars 1bn-plus a UN team of experts has said is needed up to March. UN
officials say that hundreds of thousands of people are at risk from hunger,
cold and disease in the Balkan winter.
More than 600,000 refugees in Croatia have no adequate shelter and more than
2m people in Bosnia are living in war-torn areas, many without water,
heating or even window covers. After the first snows, many mountain roads
will be impassable for relief convoys.
Mrs Sadako Ogata, UN High Commissioner for Refugees, who presented the
appeal in Geneva, said the international community had to act now: 'Time is
short and thousands of lives are at stake.'
The UN call for funds covers 'life-threatening priority needs' for the 2.7m
people directly affected by the conflict in the former Yugoslavia. Half of
these are children and the rest mostly women, elderly and disabled. Almost
2m have fled their homes and others remain trapped in cities under siege.
</TEXT>
