<PROFILE>_AN-CIFAEAACFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920905
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 92 / Money Markets: Heavy trading
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sterling futures prices gyrated wildly yesterday after the announcement of
poor employment figures upset the bullish mood that had followed the UK
government's announcement of a Ecu 10bn borrowing to support sterling.
In the early morning, the September and December contracts traded up to
89.83 and 89.89 respectively as sterling continued to rally on the foreign
exchanges, rising above the DM2.82 level.
However, the Bank of Italy's announcement that it would raise its discount
rate by 1.75 percentage points to defend the ailing lira further highlighted
that the UK is the one country in the exchange rate mechanism that has not
altered rates as a means of controlling currency movements. Both contracts
gradually descended to 89.62 and 89.63 at around lunchtime in London.
The very bad non-farm payroll figure in the US sharply depressed the dollar
and pushed sterling to a low of DM2.7750. The contracts were therefore
further depressed, reaching lows of 89.56 and 89.54. But they later
rebounded with the currency. The September contract closed 8 basis points
down on the day at 89.70 and the December contract was down 10 basis points
at 89.68.
Trading in the cash market took similar turns. One year money peaked at 10
1/2 per cent following the US employment figure but later closed at 10 7/16
per cent, which was  3/16 per cent down from the previous close. The offered
rate for 3-months money, which is a guide to where the market thinks base
rates are moving, closed softer on the day at 10 3/8 per cent from a
previous close of 10 1/2 per cent.
One discount house trader said that yesterday's moves made it extremely
difficult to trade in the market. 'All you can do is stick to a long term
view and hold to it, though that's difficult right now,' he said. A clearing
bank trader was confident that the gyration were over, however: 'There is a
new confidence in the government's determination to hold sterling at
DM2.95,' he said.
The Bank of England's operations were straightforward. The Bank forecast a
shortage of Pounds 450m and, at lunchtime, bought Pounds 444m of Band 1 bank
bills at 9 7/8 per cent. The Bank did not operate in the afternoon.
</TEXT>
