<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / International Company News: Modest rise in sales for US
stores
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MOST OF the big US retailers saw only modest increases in comparable store
sales during August - further indication of the sluggish recovery in the
economy.
However, a number warned comparisons with August 1991 had been affected by
the relatively late Labor Day this year, which marks the official end of
summer and children's return to school. Some 'back-to-school' spending, it
was suggested, had been pushed into the current month.
'The impact of this calendar shift was most evident in apparel and other
back-to-school merchandise in those sections of the country where school
openings have been delayed,' commented K mart, the large discount retailer.
K mart saw a 1.7 per cent increase during August, with the general
merchandise side posting a 0.6 per cent improvement and the speciality
chains - ranging from the Payless drug stores to Waldenbooks - advancing by
4.7 per cent.
At Woolworth, there was a 2.5 per cent rise in domestic same store sales,
while Sears reported a 3.5 per cent improvement.
Among the big department store groups, Dallas-based J C Penney fared well,
with a 12.4 per cent rise in same store sales in its main division, and a
12.6 per cent gain at its drug store outlets. But at Neiman Marcus, there
was a more restrained 3.9 per cent rise in comparable store sales; at Dayton
Hudson, a flat performance; and at May Department Stores, a 1.2 per cent
decline.
Wal-Mart, the expansion-minded discount chain which is now the nation's
largest retailer, managed a creditable 10 per cent improvement in same store
sales - although even this was slightly below the 12 per cent improvement
seen in the first seven months to end-August. At The Gap, the fashion
retailer, same-store sales gained 6 per cent.
</TEXT>
