<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / International Capital Markets: Royal Trust chief executive
to quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michael Cornelissen is stepping down after nine turbulent years as chief
executive of Royal Trust, the Canadian financial institution controlled by
the Toronto branch of the Bronfman family.
The company, which is Canada's second biggest trust company with operations
in Europe and the US, said yesterday that Mr Cornelissen, 49, will leave his
post before its annual meeting next April. He plans to move from Toronto to
Vancouver. A successor will be appointed later.
Mr Cornelissen, a hard-driving South African-born accountant, has been chief
executive since August 1983. After spectacular growth in Europe and the US
under his stewardship during the 1980s, Royal Trust has recently suffered
large loan losses and has been forced to pull in its horns. Its US
subsidiary, Seattle-based Pacific First Bank, is being sold.
The company yesterday heaped praise on Mr Cornelissen. He is widely credited
with breathing new vigour into Royal Trust, which had a reputation for
stodginess before it was taken over by the Bronfmans in the early 1980s.
But questions have been raised in recent years about Mr Cornelissen's
aggressive management style during a period of slower growth and
retrenchment. His two major international acquisitions, of Dow Chemical's
financial services arm in 1986, and of a string of US savings and loan
institutions in 1989/90, have turned out to be costly mistakes.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
