<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / Government faces up to training shake-up: Lisa Wood looks at
pressures on Gillian Shephard as she shapes the future of schemes for
jobless people
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MIKE O'REILLY, director of human resources at Wimpey, one of Britain's
biggest construction companies, believes the government should hurry up and
decide what it wants from its training scheme for the long term unemployed.
He believes the scheme - Employment Training - is not creating the skilled
workers that Wimpey needs, partly because of the restrictions on who is
eligible.
He is planning a campaign, supported by other building company training
executives, to persuade the government to extend the scheme to all
unemployed people.
Such a campaign is timely. Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment secretary, will
today begin receiving submissions to her wide-ranging review of government
programmes for the adult unemployed. Under review is ET itself, Employment
Action, the benefit plus temporary work scheme for the long-term unemployed,
and Job Clubs, which the government claims is a cost-effective way of
getting people back to work.
Just how radical the review is will emerge over the next couple of months,
with Mrs Shephard likely to be constrained by political and financial
pressures. She will face calls from Tory backbenchers who want to follow the
US example of Workfare under which only those long-term unemployed
undertaking community work receive benefit.
Civil servants have given Workfare a lukewarm response, not least because it
would be extremely difficult to run sufficient schemes to mop up the large
numbers of people eligible. It is understood that the government has
similarly been backing off the proposal to cut the entitlement to
unemployment benefit from one year to six months.
Providers of training hope that the review will concentrate on quality, to
equip the UK for any upturn in the economy.
But the Department of Employment - like others in Whitehall - is likely to
be subject to funding cuts in the current Public Expenditure Survey. ET will
be the most vulnerable scheme because the other main training programme,
Youth Training, the scheme for those aged 16 to 18, carries a guarantee of a
place to all who want one. It is politically sensitive for the gov-ernment
that this is met. ET carries no such formal guarantee.
As important is the fact that ET is criticised as ripe for reform. Started
in 1988, before the recession, its clients are mainly low-skill individuals
of whom 47 per cent are inner-city residents who worked in the old
manufacturing industries. About 104,000 people are doing ET in England and
Wales.
The scheme's record is poor. Of those completing schemes only 36 per cent go
into jobs or self employment or full-time training and about 30 per cent get
a qualification.
ET is viewed by many of its clients as a government device to get them off
the unemployment register, while many training providers claim they are
unable to give quality training because the Pounds 800m-a-year scheme is
underfunded.
The Unemployment Unit, a research organisation, said that while job entry
rates could be explained partly by the weakness of regional employment
conditions, qualification rates reflected the poor quality of the training
people were receiving.
The 82 Training and Enterprise Councils (Tecs) in England and Wales, which
administer government funded training schemes, want a freer hand in who they
can train on ET. In their submission to Mrs Shephard they are expected to
point to a range of alternatives, such as varying periods of training for
different groups depending on their needs. Short intensive courses could
assist skilled individuals recently made unemployed. More disadvantaged
people could have longer training than at present.
Last week G10, the group of 10 Tec chairmen who represent the views of Tecs
to government, made it clear that further cuts to their training budgets
were unacceptable. It is likely, however, that if asked to make funding
choices they would opt to have fewer people trained but to a higher quality.
Mr Stuart Bishell, managing director of Astra Training, which took over the
former government Skillcentres and which is the largest provider of ET
training, said: 'We want the focus of government spending on training to be
on those people who are most likely to benefit from it most rapidly.'
Such a move is being considered by the Department of Employment. Mrs
Shephard could argue that in return for cash constraints the Treasury should
allow Tecs greater freedom of choice and allow her department to negotiate
targets. Tecs for example could be paid varying amounts for training
different groups.
But the Treasury wants the existing rules on ET eligibility tightened, not
relaxed. At present Tecs are only allowed to put other groups on ET after
satisfying demand from the long-term unemployed.
Another option being considered by the government is to expand Employment
Action. EA, set up a year ago, is cheaper than ET but has not been a great
success. At present about 23,000 out of 30,000 places are filled. Whether
this scheme could be expanded without some element of compulsion is
debatable.
Tecs would certainly like greater ability to mix and match programmes to
meet the needs of their catchment areas - but not if that means less funding
for training. It is a demand that government will find hard to meet.
</TEXT>
