<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / Lib Dems outline plan for greater UN powers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UNITED Nations should be given the power to intervene in countries'
domestic affairs, as part of a thorough-going reform of its working, the
Liberal Democrats said yesterday.
Sir David Steel, the party's foreign affairs spokesman, said the criticisms
made of the UN over its role in the former Yugoslavia and in Somalia
reflected the unwillingness of the international community to consider
changes to nations' attitudes to sovereignty following the end of the cold
war.
'The UN as an organisation has never lived up to the dreams of its founders
nor to its charter,' he said at the launch of Beyond The Nation State, a
document to be discussed at the party's annual conference later this month.
The paper envisages the more systematic development of a range of sanctions
against countries which breach criteria on, for instance, human rights and
the environment. The UN is urged to improve its information gathering and
set up a permanent peacekeeping force.
The paper proposes that Japan should become a member of the Security Council
and that in due course the French and British membership should be replaced
by a single European Community seat.
Sir David said that if the UN was going to be more effective 'you have got
to allow a supra-national authority to invade national authority'.
</TEXT>
