<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Early Dow rise lost as jobs
data are awaited
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices ended little changed yesterday after coming off early
morning highs as traders and investors positioned themselves for today's
important jobs data and the approaching Labor Day lengthened weekend, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished just 1.89 up at 3,292.20, after
having stood 20 points ahead at the day's peak. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500
ended unchanged at 417.98, although the American SE composite gained a net
2.37 at 385.10 and the Nasdaq composite 3.63 at 574.88. New York SE turnover
was fairly heavy at 212.5m shares.
The sharp rise in Tokyo stocks overnight and a bright showing on European
bourses laid the groundwork for a firm opening in New York. Japanese stocks
have now climbed 30 per cent from their recent floor, an indication, said
some analysts yesterday, that the prolonged downturn in the Tokyo market may
be over.
Apart from Tokyo's advance, investors were keeping their eyes firmly on
today's employment report for August. The consensus among analysts is that
last month's non-farm payrolls rose by 155,000, although most of the
increase is expected to have been related to temporary hiring under a
federal summer jobs programme. Overall, the picture is expected to remain
flat.
Citicorp slipped Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 16 1/4 on reports that a study by
the Comptroller of the Currency had discovered serious management and credit
quality problems in the bank's mortgage business.
One of the busiest stocks was Gap Stores, which fell Dollars 2 1/8 to
Dollars 33 1/2 in turnover of 3m shares after the company reported that
comparable same-store sales rose 6 per cent in August, a figure that
disappointed the market. May Department Stores shed Dollars 1 to Dollars 59
1/4 after announcing that same-store sales were down 1.2 per cent in August.
The company blamed the fall on the shift in the Labor Day holiday this year.
The repercussions of Hurricane Andrew continued to take their toll. Lennar
Homes dropped a further Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 23 1/2 as investors feared
that more home owners in south Florida who lost their houses in the
hurricane may sue the company for shoddy construction. Lennar says the suit
is totally without merit.
On the Nasdaq market, larger capitalised technology stocks continued to lead
the way with solid gains. Intel rose Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 62 1/4 ,
Microsoft Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 76 5/8 , Borland Dollars  3/4 to Dollars
43 3/4 and Sun Microsystems Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 27 5/8 , but Apple eased
Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 47 3/4 .
Canada
PROGRESS in Canada's constitutional talks helped Toronto stocks withstand
the late retreat on Wall Street. Although slipping from its midday high, the
TSE 300 index finished 16.5 ahead at 3,453.2 and volume was heavy at 36.5m
shares. Advances led declines by 359 to 213.
Also adding to the bullish tone on the Toronto market was the stronger US
dollar, cuts in leading Canadian banks' prime rates and gains in overseas
markets.
</TEXT>
