<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Paris takes the lead in the
continental rally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MILAN missed out on a continental rally, stoked by a firmer dollar, less
anxiety over the French referendum, and opening gains in the UK market,
writes Our Markets Staff.
PARIS's futures-driven rally was frustrated by computer problems which
closed down trading for several hours. The CAC-40 index ended up 69.05 or 4
per cent to 1,780.46, its highest close in four weeks. Turnover was
relatively heavy at FFr2.3bn.
Dealers said that cautious optimism about the Maastricht referendum, the
rally on the UK stock market and a firmer sterling prompted a flood of buy
orders from London and domestic institutions. An absence of poor corporate
results and rumours that the German government was considering fiscal
advantages to encourage investment in eastern Germany also fuelled the rise
in share prices.
Among the day's winners were Michelin, up FFr13.80 or 7 per cent to
FFr204.40 and Euro Disney, FFr4.90 or 6.4 per cent to FFr81.90. Total
bounced back FFr10.40 to FFr205.50 in the wake of its recent losses. Nomura
and Merrill Lynch issued 'buy' notes on the oil refiner yesterday.
FRANKFURT saw more short-covering, and a rise in sympathy with other
markets. The DAX index ended 24.08 higher at 1,530.75; some of this
reflected gains reported in Frankfurt's post-bourse on Wednesday, but there
was a similar extension of the uptrend yesterday afternoon.
Volume rose from DM3.8bn to DM4.3bn. Major blue chip advances included
Siemens, up DM10.70 to DM594.50, Bayer's DM4.70 to DM268.50, DM12.30 to
DM621.80 for Daimler and DM7.10 to DM319.50 for Volkswagen.
Deutsche Bank, too, saw solid interest, gaining DM10.60 to DM612.60. Dealers
said that the bank had held an analysts' meeting on Wednesday, which had a
broadly neutral impact.
MILAN was dragged lower at the opening by heavy selling by one of the larger
domestic brokers, and dealers remained pessimistic about the market in spite
of a late recovery in prices. The Comit index fell 3.91 to 371.43, a new low
for the year, in turnover estimated at more than L100bn after Wednesday's
L92.7bn.
Rumours of a capital increase dragged the widely-held Mediobanca down by
L435 or 4.6 per cent to L9,095. The stock has also been dogged by persistent
rumours about its veteran chairman, Mr Enrico Cuccia.
Italmobiliare remained on the sellers' list, falling L2,010 or 6.4 per cent
to L29,500.
Benetton was brought off the day's low of L10,100 by its first-half results
which were in line with expectations. The stock closed L150 higher at
L10,500.
AMSTERDAM rose 1.7 per cent, investors moving in to buy shares as the dollar
strengthened. Some relatively good corporate earnings news also helped. The
CBS Tendency index added 1.8 to 110.3.
ING put on Fl 2.40 or 5.5 per cent on news of a 7 per cent rise in
first-half net, while Ahold dipped 40 cents to Fl 75.70 on disappointing
first-half profit growth of 6 per cent.
MADRID bet on a French Yes vote on Maastricht, the general index rising
6.48, or 3.1 per cent to 216.30. Banks included a Central Hispano rise of
Pta230 or 7.7 per cent to Pta3,230, after it talked of reducing the number
of its branches by a net 500 to 2,500 next year.
Dealers said that this rise was not volume-driven, and that individual gains
were erratic. In construction stocks, Uralita, which on Wednesday reported
first half profits of Pta14bn after extraordinary profits of Pta21bn, rose
Pta69, or 10.7 per cent, to Pta715.
STOCKHOLM recovered in moderate trading, supported by falling domestic
interest rates and gains in foreign markets. The Affarsvarlden General Index
rose 7.5 to 753.9 in turnover of SKr400m after SKr458m.
New bankruptcies in the real estate sector continued to plague the banking
section, with S-E Banken falling to a year's low of SKr14.5, down SKr0.5.
OSLO's recovery, with the all-share index up 1.8 per cent to 313.02, was
marred by a NKr7.5 drop to NKr32.5 in Aker, which said that its Norwegian
Contractors subsidiary would incur a 1992 loss of NKr400m after
miscalculating the costs of installing a concrete platform at the Heidrun
gas and oil field.
BRUSSELS bounced back from its recent losses, the Bel-20 index ending 20.70
or 2 per cent higher at 1,066.86. Petrofina closed BFr210 or 2.5 per cent
higher at BFr8,560.
