<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / International Company News: Western Mining tumbles into the
red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WESTERN Mining Corporation (WMC), the Australian mining group, yesterday
blamed lower metals prices and an abnormal loss of ADollars 200m for a
consolidated net loss of ADollars 8.5m (USDollars 6.07m) in the year to
end-June. Last time the group turned in a profit of ADollars 276m.
Sales were down 6.8 per cent to ADollars 1.4bn.
The board cut the final dividend to five cents, fully franked, compared with
11 cents in the second half of the previous year. This made a total for the
year of 11 cents, fully franked, against 24 cents.
The result was towards the top end of market expectations, and the shares
gained four cents to close at ADollars 5.02.
WMC said consolidated operating profit was down 30 per cent to ADollars
205m, mainly because of lower prices for nickel and oil, and lower earnings
from gold because of lower production.
Equity-accounted net profit, which includes the group's interests in
associated companies, fell to ADollars 161m from ADollars 362m in the
previous year, mainly due to a decline in the contribution from Alcoa to
ADollars 141m from ADollars 278m. The group said Alcoa was performing well
in a difficult market.
Amcor, the Australian paper and packaging group, has defied recession in its
main markets, registering a 29 per cent increase in consolidated net profit
to ADollars 223m (USDollars 160.3m) in the year to end-June. Turnover rose
23 per cent to ADollars 4.1bn.
The board declared a final dividend of 15 cents a share, franked to 95 per
cent. The interim dividend was 14 cents, franked to 64 per cent. The total
of 29 cents compares with 27 cents in the previous year.
