<DATE>920904
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / International Capital Markets: US Treasury to test single
price auction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Treasury plans an immediate start to its experiment with single price
bond auctions with this month's auction of two and five-year notes.
The Treasury plans a year-long test of the single price auction formula,
replacing its current multiple price system for all monthly sales of the two
and five-year notes.
Under the current auction format, the Treasury determines a cut-off price at
which it can sell all the securities it put up for auction, but successful
bidders must pay the price specified in their bids.
With the single price formula, the Treasury will determine a cut-off price
in the same way, but all successful bidders will pay this price.
Mr Jerome Powell, undersecretary for finance at the Treasury, said academic
research suggested this should result in more competitive bidding and should
therefore reduce the US government's borrowing costs.
'You are letting people pay a lower price than they bid or get a higher
yield than they bid, which would appear to cost us money. On the other hand,
everyone bids more aggressively,' Mr Powell said.
Treasury officials argue that securities buyers have an incentive under the
current system to aim for the market consensus. This leads many buyers to
bid through the big dealers who have the most information about the market,
because if they bid too high they will end up owning bonds or notes for
which they have paid more than the market price - the winner's curse.
'The theory is that people would bid more aggressively because no-one would
suffer from this winner's curse,' Mr Powell said.
The Treasury plans to judge the success of the single price experiment at
reducing its borrowing costs by comparing the volume of bids with the volume
of securities auctioned, and the auction yield with the yield of the same
securities in the 'when-issued' market before the auction takes place.
It will also examine the number of competitive bidders, the concentration of
awards with certain firms and the yield dispersion of accepted bids.
Dealers expect the Treasury to sell around Dollars 15bn of two-year notes
and Dollars 10.5bn of five-year notes, the same volume as last month, at the
first single price auction in three weeks' time.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
