<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Cookson recovers to Pounds 34m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COOKSON, the industrial materials group, underlined its continuing recovery
yesterday by announcing a substantial increase in interim profits following
its restructuring.
The pre-tax figure doubled from Pounds 17m to Pounds 34m in the six months
to June 30, while earnings per share bounced back to 4.2p (0.9p). The
interim dividend is unchanged at 3p.
Turnover from continuing operations grew by 4 per cent to Pounds 605m
(Pounds 581m). Excluding acquisitions, the increase was 2 per cent,
reflecting 'difficult trading conditions' caused by the world recession.
Total turnover, including discontinued operations, was Pounds 609m (Pounds
676m).
The company has focused on controlling costs and overheads. Employee numbers
have been further reduced in all divisions, and stand at 12,500, down from a
peak of 16,000. Redundancy costs of Pounds 1.2m compared to Pounds 1.6m last
time.
Mr Robert Malpas, chairman, said the results showed Cookson was continuing
its recovery.
Operating profits rose 39 per cent to Pounds 43m. The figure of Pounds 31m
for the previous first half included Pounds 3m from discontinued operations.
All four reorganised divisions - electronic materials, ceramics, engineered
products and plastics - reported improved profits.
A significant reduction in the level of borrowings during 1991 resulted in
reduced interest charges of Pounds 9m (Pounds 14m). However, at the end of
June net borrowings were Pounds 211m, compared to Pounds 142m at the end of
December, and gearing increased from 33 per cent to 53 per cent.
The increase in borrowings was attributed to the seasonal rise in working
capital and the cost of acquiring the additional 50 per cent stake in
Stern-Leach, which resulted in the consolidation of Stern-Leach's Dollars
66m (Pounds 33.1m) borrowings into the balance sheet.
COMMENT
Cookson is a recovery stock making good on its promise without any help from
trading conditions. The company's new - and streamlined - senior management
team has made creditable progress towards stripping the unwieldy group back
to its core but they have further to go. Expect more disposals businesses,
though not at fire sale prices. Full-year pre-tax profits are projected at
about Pounds 72m, for a prospective p/e of 10.5. The shares stood last night
36p below their 170p high for the year. If trading conditions improve they
could recover quickly that lost ground despite some dollar translation
risks.
</TEXT>
